{
  "card_id": "trendline_liquidity",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Trendline Liquidity",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "Smart Money Concepts (SMC)",
  "definition": "A liquidity pattern where price forms a series of small break of structures along a diagonal trendline, creating a cluster of stop-loss orders from retail traders near that trendline. Smart money targets this liquidity pool, sweeping it before reversing to continue the dominant trend.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Price initially forms a valid break of structure (BOS) in the dominant trend direction, leaving an unmitigated supply or demand zone and a fair value gap (inefficiency).",
    "After the BOS, price retraces and then creates a sequence of small break of structures with minor swing highs and lows closely spaced, forming a clear diagonal trendline.",
    "The trendline connects successive minor lows in a bullish scenario or minor highs in a bearish scenario.",
    "The repetitive small BOS movements attract retail traders who enter on trendline bounces, placing stop-loss orders just beyond the trendline (below for longs, above for shorts).",
    "A concentrated liquidity pool forms along the trendline, providing a target for smart money to sweep before a larger trend continuation."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Wait for the price to break the trendline and sweep the accumulated liquidity (stop-losses). In a bullish scenario, after the sweep below the trendline and a fill of the inefficiency, look for a long entry from the demand zone below the sweep. In a bearish scenario, after the sweep above the trendline and an inefficiency fill, look for a short entry from the supply zone above. Enter only after the liquidity sweep to align with smart money, increasing trade probability.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering a trade before the liquidity sweep occurs, exposing to stop-loss hunting by smart money.",
    "Treating the trendline as a reliable support/resistance without accounting for the liquidity pool, leading to premature entries.",
    "Failing to wait for the inefficiency (fair value gap) fill and the touch of the demand/supply zone after the sweep, missing the optimal entry point."
  ],
